  ],
  "buggy_functions": [
    "__rpc_execute"
  ],
  "confidence": 0.85,
  "reasoning": "The bug is a race condition in the RPC scheduler where a fatal signal can cause the synchronous RPC call to return -ERESTARTSYS even when the RPC has completed successfully. At lines 783-792 in __rpc_execute(), when out_of_line_wait_on_bit() returns -ERESTARTSYS due to a signal, the code immediately calls rpc_exit(task, -ERESTARTSYS) without checking if the RPC_TASK_QUEUED bit has already been cleared by the RPC completion handler (rpc_make_runnable()). If the RPC response arrived just before the signal, the task's RPC_TASK_QUEUED bit would already be cleared (meaning the RPC completed successfully), but the task is still exiting with -ERESTARTSYS instead of continuing the loop to process the completed RPC. The fix should be to check if RPC_IS_QUEUED(task) is still true before calling rpc_exit with -ERESTARTSYS. If the task is no longer queued, the RPC has completed and the loop should continue to allow the response to be processed instead of returning an error. This explains why NFS inode revalidation fails with error -512 (ERESTARTSYS) even though tcpdump shows the server replied without error."
}

